              "criterion": "Correct expression for $u_2$ e.g. $k - 7$ with no incorrect work seen. Must be seen in part (a). Allow e.g. $u_2 = 1 \\times k - 7 + 7$ or e.g. $u_2 = 1 \\times k - 7 + 7$ or e.g. $u_2 = 1 \\times k - 7 + 7$"
            },
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Attempts to use the recurrence formula to reach the 5th term but condone consistent use of (n + 1) for n on the $(n-1)$ term. Allow even if any slips mean their sequence is not of order 4."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1*",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Obtains $u_5 = 7$ with no errors or omissions. The \"$u_5 =$\" must appear at some point but allow e.g. $u_{4+1} = $"
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "For reference the terms are: $u_1 = 7, u_2 = k - 7, u_3 = 2k - 7, u_4 = 7 - k, u_5 = 7$. (a) Alternatives: $u_{n+1} = k u_n - u_{n-1}$. B1: Implied by $u_2 = k u_1 - u_0$. M1: Attempts to use the recurrence formula to reach the 5th term but condone use of (n + 1) for n on the $(n-1)$ term as above. A1*: Fully correct work to reach $u_5 = 7$. (Allow the above approach to be used with a made up k or a wrong k as the result is independent of k). $u_5 = 7 \\implies u_4 = k - 7 \\implies u_3 = k - (k - 7) \\implies u_2 = k - (k - (k - 7)) \\implies u_1 = k - (k - (k - (k - 7)))$. Hence true. B1: $u_4 = k - 7$. M1: Attempts to use the recurrence formula correctly backwards to reach the 1st term but condone use of (n + 1) for n on the $(n-1)$ term as above. A1*: Fully correct work to reach $u_1 = 7$ with a (minimal) conclusion."
        },
