          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Correct numerical attempt for the required sum using their k. May be implied by the correct answer or the correct ft answer unless an incorrect method is seen. Condone $150 \\times 30/4$ or $75 \\times 15$ or $37.5 \\times 30$ following a correct sequence and the correct value of k. Allow any equivalent correct method."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1cso",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "For 1125 from correct work and a correct sequence."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "Marks in (c) are only available if their sequence is of order 4. Note this has been seen more than once for the GP sum following $299 = 250/20$: $(20(1 - 12.5^{300}))/(1 - 1.008483032)$ and scores M0 as it suggests $(a(1-r^n))/(1-r)$ has been used. For reference the correct sequence is: n=1, $u_n=7$; n=2, $u_n=k-7$; n=3, $u_n=2k-7$; n=4, $u_n=7-k$. Value (with k=15): 7, 8, 23, -8. An unusual but correct method in (c) is: $\\sum_{r=1}^{150} u_r = 38 \\times (7 + (15-7)) + 37 \\times (7 + (15-7)) = 1125$. Example – Candidates who consistently use $u_{n+1} = u_n - k + u_{n-1}$. This gives: (a) $u_1=7, u_2=k+7, u_3=-7, u_4=k-7, u_5=7$ which scores B0M1A0. (b) $\\sum_{r=1}^{4} u_r = 7+k+7-7+k-7 = 30 \\implies 2k = 30 \\implies k=15$ which scores M1A0. (c) $\\sum_{r=1}^{150} u_r = 37 \\times 30 + 7 + (15+7) = 1139$ which scores M1A0. For reference this incorrect sequence is: n=1, $u_n=7$; n=2, $u_n=k+7$; n=3, $u_n=-7$; n=4, $u_n=k-7$. Value (with k=15): 7, 22, -7, 8."
        }
      ]
