      ],
      "guidance": "Alternative: $\\log_4(12-2x) = 2 + 2\\log_4(x+1) \\implies \\log_4(12-2x) = \\log_4(16) + \\log_4(x+1)^2 \\implies \\log_4(12-2x) = \\log_4(16(x+1)^2)$. Then follow main scheme. Score as: B1: $\\log_4(x+1)^2 = \\log_4(x+1)$. M1: Uses correct index law e.g. $a^b \\times a^c = a^{b+c}$. Then follow main scheme. Special Case: Beware incorrect log work which leads to the correct answer: $\\log_4(12-2x) - 2\\log_4(x+1) = 2 \\implies \\log_4(12-2x) - \\log_4(x+1)^2 = 2 \\implies (12-2x) = 16(x+1)^2$. This scores B1M0A0M1A0. Allow this SC if no combination of logs is shown at all, but the correct quadratic is produced. e.g. $\\log_4(12-2x) = 2 + 2\\log_4(x+1) \\implies (12-2x) = 16(x+1)^2$ etc. or e.g. $\\log_4(12-2x) - \\log_4(16) = \\log_4(x+1)^2 \\implies (12-2x)/16 = (x+1)^2$ etc. Could both score B1M0A0M1A0. Special Case: Beware incorrect work removing logs which leads to the correct answer: $\\log_4(12-2x) - 2\\log_4(x+1) = 2 \\implies (12-2x) = 4^2(x+1)^2$. This scores B1M1A0M1A0."
