          "guidance": "Examples: $x^2 + 9/x^2 = 13 - 3x^2 \\implies x^4 - 10x^2 + 9 = 0 \\implies x = 1, 3$ Scores M1A1M0A0. $x^2 + 9/x^2 = 13 - 3x^2 \\implies x^4 - 10x^2 + 9 = 0 \\implies x^2 = 1, 9 \\implies x = 1, 9$ Scores M1A1M1A0 (BOD). Attempts to solve $x^4 - 10x^2 + 9 = 0$ by identifying roots/factors and then using e.g. long division should be sent to review. Part (a) may also be done without obtaining a quartic: $y = x^2 + 9/x^2, y = 13 - 3x^2 \\implies x^2 + 9/x^2 = 13 - 3x^2 \\implies 4x^2 - 13 + 9/x^2 = 0 \\implies (x^2 - 9/x^2)(x^2 - 1/x^2) = 0$. M1: Solves simultaneously and attempts to factorise to $(x^2 - \\alpha/x^2)(x^2 - \\beta/x^2) = 0$. A1: Correct factorisation. M1: Attempts to solve via $x^2$. A1: x = 1 and x = 3. Both correct and no other values. Condone any confusion with which is P and which is Q and condone e.g. P = 1, Q = 3. Part (a) may also be done via y e.g.: $y = x^2 + 9/x^2, y = 13 - 3x^2 \\implies x^2 = y - 9/x^2 \\implies y = (y-9/x^2) + 9/(y-9/x^2)$. M1: Solves simultaneously to obtain a 3TQ in y. A1: Correct 3TQ in y. M1: Solves their 3TQ in y and uses at least one value of y to find a value for x. A1: x = 1 and x = 3. Both correct and no other values. Condone any confusion with which is P and which is Q and condone e.g. P = 1, Q = 3."
